\subsection{The minimal example}
The second example we consider is the dynamical black holes which were found in certain minimal coupled Einstein-scalar gravity in four dimensions
\cite{Zhang:2014sta}. The Lagrangian is given by
\setlength\arraycolsep{2pt} \begin{eqnarray}
{\cal L} &=& \sqrt{-g} \Big(R - \ft12(\partial\phi)^2 - V(\phi)\Big),\cr
V&=& -2g^2 (\cosh\phi + 2) - 2\alpha (2\phi + \phi \cosh\phi - 3 \sinh\phi)\,.
\label{lagmini}
\end{eqnarray}
The scalar potential has a stationary point $\phi=0$ with small $\phi$ expansion

It follows that the scalar has a mass square $m^2=2g^2$ which is above the Breitenlohner-Freedman bound ($m_{BF}^2=-{\textstyle{\frac{\scriptstyle 9}{\scriptstyle 4} } } g^2$) in AdS space-time with $g^2>0$.
